abstract: A recent circular of the Greman Minister of War has exhorted Colonels to urge their subalterns toward the study of modern languages. abstract: LONDON, May 3.--A dispatch from Kabul says: "The military force here now is again so strong that any operations can be undertaken, and it is likely that it will be required. The population of Kabul, comprising partisans of the different Sirdars, is always ready for an excitement."

abstract: BALTIMORE, May 29.--South of Mason and Dixon's line the Sage of Gramercy Park is viewed by all Democrats with aversion. His candidacy has been looked upon as inevitable by many, and still is by some, while all hope that something will turn up before the Cincinnati Convention meets to throw him off the track without his influence being lost to the Democratic Party.

abstract: LONDON, May 15.--Several American and a dozen foreign artists have found favor in the eyes of Sir Coutts Lindsay and his counsel and been admitted to the Grosvenor Gallery. Among the former, Augustus Saint Gaudens, of New-York, and among the latter Bastien Le Page, of Paris, may be said to carry off the honors for sculpture and painting, respectively.

abstract: PATERSON, N.J., May 29.--The oldest farmers in this part of New-Jersey declare that they never saw such a prolonged drought at this season of the year. Only two light showers have fallen this month--one on the night of May 22, when 0.11 of an inch came down, and one on the morning of May 28, when the quantity could scarcely be measured.
